<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900615-0048</DOCNO><DOCID>900615-0048.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>06/15/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   Sandamp;P LOWERED its ratings on debt issued by Chrysler andFord, and affirmed ratings for GM. The agency, which citedgrowing competition and soft auto demand, downgraded Ford'ssenior debt to double-A-minus and Chrysler's totriple-B-minus, one notch above speculative grade.   ---</LP><TEXT>   A serious credit crunch extends well beyond the realestate industry and appears to be worsening, CommerceSecretary Mosbacher said.   ---   Reebok said its biggest shareholder, Pentland Group ofLondon, plans to sell its 31.5% stake. The sneaker companypromptly adopted a &quot;poison pill&quot; takeover defense.   ---   Gold prices tumbled on Saudi sales of the metal and theprospect of sales by the Soviets to raise cash. Central banksswooped into the market with big buy orders to halt thedecline.                                                                                                          Stock prices eased amid growing concern about corporateearnings, while bonds gained. The Dow Jones industrials fell1.48 to 2928.22.   ---   The Soviet Union's economic uncertainty is hindering thecountry's efforts to secure new Western loans as waryBritish, Swiss and German bankers demand steeply higherrates.   ---   CBS and ABC adopted NBC's plan to reduce the audience sizethat the network guarantees advertisers.   ---   The Big Board's acceleration of plans for off-hours stocktrading was triggered by fears about competing efforts byover-the-counter dealers and by the Big Board's own members.   ---   Producer prices rose 0.3% in May, reversing three monthsof decline. The report suggests that inflation is likely tocontinue at a moderate pace.   ---   Orix won the rights to buy 74 Airbus planes that Braniffhad ordered, and plans to becomes Japan's firstaircraft-leasing concern.   ---   Southland sweetened its exchange offer to bondholders byabout $200 million. The plan would slash the Thompsonfamily's equity stake.   ---   The thrift bailout will require an additional $30 billionto $50 billion in funding next year, Brady projected,generating criticism from Democrats.                                                                                                          The Resolution Trust Corp. can override state laws topermit the sale of failed Sandamp;Ls to banks, a judge ruled.   ---   The Senate approved a resolution to cap fiscal 1991discretionary spending at this year's level.   ---   Philips warned that second-quarter profit will fall&quot;appreciably&quot; and that full-year results will be &quot;very low.&quot;The Dutch electronics giant is in the midst of a managementshake-up.   ---   U.S. auto makers intend to boost output in the thirdquarter, despite disappointing sales. The plans reflect leaninventories and labor concerns.   ---   Honeywell petitioned the government to halt imports ofMinolta automatic-focusing cameras, saying they violate theU.S. company's patents.   ---   A $55 billion farm bill cleared a House panel. It includesa new policy on soil and water conservation.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 135,770,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2928.22, off 1.48; transportation 1195.44, off 9.12;utilities 213.09, off 0.88.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3459.37, up12.93.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 130.49, off 1.89;spot index 129.84, off 1.11.   Dollar: 154.17 yen, off 0.58; 1.6935 marks, up 0.0070.</TEXT></DOC>